{{Catalan language}}

'''Catalan''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|æ|t|əl|æ|n}};<ref name="dictionary.reference.com">Laurie Bauer, 2007, ''The Linguistics Student’s Handbook'', Edinburgh; also {{IPAc-en|k|æ|t|ə|ˈ|l|æ|n}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|æ|t|əl|ən}}[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Catalan]</ref> [[Endonym|autonym]]: ''català'' {{IPA-ca|kətəˈɫa|}} or {{IPA-ca|kataˈɫa|}}) is a [[Romance languages|Romance language]] named for its origins in [[Principality of Catalonia|Catalonia]], in what is nowadays northeastern [[Spain]] and adjoining parts of [[France]]. It is the national and only official language of [[Andorra]],{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} and a co-official language of the Spanish [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous communities]] of [[Catalonia]], the [[Balearic Islands]], and the [[Valencian Community]] (as [[Valencian language|'''Valencian''']], with its own standard). It also has semi-official status in the city of [[Alghero]] on the [[Italy|Italian]] island of [[Sardinia]]. It is also spoken with no official recognition in parts of the Spanish autonomous communities of [[Aragon]] ([[La Franja]]) and [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] ([[Carche]]), and in the historic French region of [[Roussillon]]/[[Northern Catalonia]], roughly equivalent to the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Pyrénées-Orientales]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2005|p=1}}

Catalan evolved from [[Vulgar Latin|common Latin]] around the eastern [[Pyrenees]] in the 9th century.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} During the [[Low Middle Ages]] it saw a golden age as the literary and dominant language of the [[Crown of Aragon]], and was widely used all over the [[Mediterranean]].{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}}{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190-191}} The union of Aragon with the other territories of [[Spain]] in 1479 marked the start of the decline of the language.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}}{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190-191}} In 1659 Spain ceded [[Northern Catalonia]] to [[France]], and Catalan was banned in both states in the early 18th century.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190-191}} 19th-century Spain saw a [[Renaixença|Catalan literary revival]],{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190-191}}{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} which culminated in the 1913 orthographic standardization, and the officialization of the language during the [[Second Spanish Republic]] (1931–39). However, the [[Francoist Spain|Francoist dictatorship]] (1939–75) banned the language again.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190-191}}

Since the [[Spanish transition to democracy]] (1975–1982), Catalan has been recognized as an official language, language of education, and language of mass media, all of which have contributed to its increased prestige.{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}} There is no parallel in Europe of such a large, [[bilingualism|bilingual]], [[Stateless nation|non-state]] speech community.{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}}

Compared to other Romance languages, Catalan dialects feature relative uniformity,{{sfn|Moll|1958|p=47}}{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|pp=634–635}} and are mutually intelligible.{{sfn|Wheeler|2005|p=1}}{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|2009|p=5}}{{sfn|Feldhausen|2010|p=5}}<ref name="ethnologue"/> They are divided into two blocks, Eastern and Western, differing mostly in pronunciation.{{sfn|Moll|1958|p=47}}{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|pp=634–635}} The terms "Catalan" and "[[Valencian language|Valencian]]" (respectively used in [[Catalonia]] and the [[Valencian Community]]) are two names for the same language.<ref name="avl.gva.es">[http://www.avl.gva.es/img/EdicionsPublicacions/AcordsGenerals/NOMENTITAT.pdf ''"Dictamen de l'Acadèmia Valenciana de la Llengua sobre els principis i criteris per a la defensa de la denominació i l'entitat del valencià"'']. Report from [[Acadèmia Valenciana de la Llengua]] about denomination and identity of Valencian.</ref>  Standard Catalan, a variety accepted by virtually all speakers,{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}} is regulated by the [[Institut d'Estudis Catalans|Institute of Catalan Studies]] (IEC).

Catalan shares many traits with its neighboring [[Romance languages]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2005|p=1}} However, despite being mostly situated in the [[Iberian Peninsula]], Catalan shows greater differences with [[Ibero-Romance]] ([[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) in terms of [[vocabulary]], [[pronunciation]], and grammar than it does with [[Gallo-Romance]] ([[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Occitan language|Occitan]], etc.).<ref name=":11">Marc Howard Ross, [http://books.google.com/books?id=Oe4popSDfW0C&printsec=frontcover&hl=en#PPA139,M1 ''Cultural Contestation in Ethnic Conflict''], page 139. Cambridge University Press, 2007.</ref>{{sfn|Jud|1925}}{{sfn|Colón|1993|pp=33–35}}{{sfn|Moll|1958|p=47}}{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=632}}{{sfn|Feldhausen|2010|p=4}}{{sfn|Schlösser|2005|p=60f}} These similarities are most notable with Occitan.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=632}}{{sfn|Feldhausen|2010|p=4}}{{sfn|Schlösser|2005|p=60f}}

Catalan has an inflectional grammar, with two [[grammatical gender|genders]] (masculine, feminine), and two [[grammatical number|numbers]] (singular, plural). Pronouns also inflected for [[grammatical case|case]], [[animacy]] and [[T–V distinction|politeness]], and can be combined in very complex ways. Verbs are split in several paradigms and are inflected for [[grammatical person|person]], [[grammatical number|number]], [[grammatical tense|tense]], [[grammatical aspect|aspect]], [[grammatical mood|mood]], and [[grammatical gender|gender]]. In terms of pronunciation, Catalan has many words ending in a wide variety consonants and some consonant clusters, in contrast with many other Romance languages.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}}

==Etymology and pronunciation==
{{Main|Etymology of Catalonia}}
The word ''Catalan'' derives from the territory of [[Catalonia]], itself of disputed etymology. The main theory suggests that ''Catalunya'' ([[Latin language|Latin]] ''Gathia Launia'') derives from the name ''Gothia'' or ''Gauthia'' ("Land of the Goths"), since the origins of the Catalan counts, lords and people were found in the [[March of Gothia]], whence ''Gothland'' → ''Gothlandia'' > ''Gothalania'' > ''Catalonia'' theoretically derived.{{sfn|García Venero|2006}}{{sfn|Burke|1900|p=154}}

In [[English language|English]], the term referring to a person first appears in mid 14th century as ''Catelaner'', followed in the 15th century as ''Catellain'' (from [[French language|French]]). It is first attested a language name by 1792. The term ''Catalonian'' is first attested in 1707. ''Catalan'' can be pronounced as {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|æ|t|əl|æ|n}}, {{IPAc-en|k|æ|t|ə|ˈ|l|æ|n}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|æ|t|əl|ən}}.<ref name="dictionary.reference.com"/>

The [[endonym]] is pronounced {{IPA|/kə.təˈɫa/}} in the Eastern Catalan dialects, and {{IPA|/ka.taˈɫa/}} in the Western dialects. In the [[Valencian Community]], the term ''valencià'' ({{IPA|/va.len.siˈa/}}) is frequently used instead. The names "Catalan" and "Valencian" are two names for the same language.{{sfn|Lledó|2011|p=334-337}}<ref name="dictalmen AVL"/> See also [[#About Valencian|status of Valencian]] below.

==History==
[[File:Greuges de Guitard Isarn.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Fragment of the ''Greuges de Guirard Isarn'' (ca.1080-1095), one of the earliest texts written almost completely in Catalan,{{sfn|Veny|1997|pp=9-18}}{{sfn|Moran|2004|pp=37-38}} predating the famous ''[[Homilies d'Organyà]]'' by a century.]]
{{further|History of Catalan}}

===Middle Ages===
{{further|Old Catalan|Phonological history of Catalan}}

By the 9th century, Catalan had evolved from [[Vulgar Latin]] on both sides of the eastern end of the [[Pyrenees]], as well as the territories of the Roman province of [[Tarraconensis]] to the south.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} From the 8th century onwards the Catalan counts extended their territory southwards and westwards at the expense of the Muslims, bringing their language with them.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} This process was given definitive impetus with the separation of the [[County of Barcelona]] from the [[Carolingian Empire]] in 988.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}}

In the 11th century, documents written in [[macaronic Latin]] begin to show Catalan elements,{{sfn|Moran|2004|pp=37–38}} with texts written almost completely in Romance appearing by 1080.{{sfn|Moran|2004|pp=37–38}} Old Catalan shared many features with [[Gallo-Romance languages|Gallo-Romance]], diverging from [[Old Occitan]] between the 11th and 14th centuries.{{sfn|Riquer|1964}}

During the 11th and 12th centuries the Catalan rulers expanded up to north of the [[Ebro river]],{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} and in the 13th century they conquered the [[Kingdom of Valencia|Land of Valencia]] and the [[Balearic Islands]].{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} The city of [[Alghero]] in [[Sardinia]] was repopulated with Catalan speakers in the 14th century. The language also reached [[Murcia]], which became Spanish-speaking in the 15th century.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190}}

[[File:Aragonese Empire 1443.svg|thumb|right|200px|The [[Crown of Aragon]] in 1443.]]
In the [[Low Middle Ages]], Catalan lived a golden age, reaching a peak of maturity and cultural plenitude.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} Examples include the work of Majorcan polymath [[Ramon Llull]] (1232–1315), the Four Great Chronicles (13th-14th centuries), and the Valencian school of poetry culminating in [[Ausiàs March]] (1397–1459).{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} By the 15th century, the city of [[Valencia]] had become the sociocultural center of the [[Crown of Aragon]], and Catalan was present all over the [[Mediterranean]] world.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} During this period, the Royal Chancery propagated a highly standardized language.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} Catalan was widely used as an official language in Sicily until the 15th century, and in Sardinia until the 17th.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190}} During this period, the language was what Costa Carreras terms "one of the 'great languages' of medieval Europe".{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}}

[[Joanot Martorell|Martorell]]'s outstanding{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} novel of chivalry ''[[Tirant lo Blanc]]'' (1490) shows a transition from Medieval to Renaissance values, something than can also be seen in [[Bernat Metge|Metge]]'s work.{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}} The first book produced with movable type in the [[Iberian Peninsula]] was printed in Catalan.<ref>''Trobes en llaors de la Verge Maria'' ("Poems of praise of the Virgin Mary") 1474.</ref>{{sfn|Costa Carreras|Yates|year=2009|pp=6–7}}

===Start of the modern era===
With the union of the crowns of [[Kingdom of Castille|Castille]] and [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]] (1479), the use of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] gradually became more prestigious.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190}} Starting in the 16th century, Catalan literature experienced a decline, the language came under the influence Spanish, and the urban and literary classes became [[bilingualism|bilingual]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=190}}

===French state: 18th to 20th centuries===
[[File:SpeakFrenchBeClean.jpg|thumb|right|200px|"Speak French, be clean", school wall in [[Ayguatébia-Talau]], 2010]]
{{See also|Language policy in France|Vergonha|Patois}}
With the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] (1659), [[Spain]] ceded the [[Northern Catalonia|northern part of Catalonia]] to [[France]], and soon thereafter the [[Northern Catalan|local Catalan varieties]] came under the influence of [[French language|French]], which in 1700 became the sole official language of the region.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crdp-montpellier.fr/cd66/artscult/fichesVauban/cdvauban/PERIODES/moyenagetempsmodernes/chateaucollioureinterdictioncatalan.pdf|title=''L'interdiction de la langue catalane en Roussillon par Louis XIV''|publisher="CRDP, Académie de Montpellier}}</ref>

Shortly after the [[French Revolution]] (1789), the [[French First Republic]] prohibited official use of, and enacted discriminating policies against, the nonstandard languages of France (''[[patois]]''), such as Catalan, Breton, Occitan, [[Flemish]], and Basque.

Following the French capture of [[Algeria]] (1833), the region saw several waves of Catalan-speaking settlers. People from the Spanish [[Alacant]] province settled around [[Oran]], while [[Algiers]] saw immigrantion from [[Northern Catalonia]] and [[Minorca]]. Their speech was known as ''patuet''. By 1911, the number of Catalan speakers was around 100,000. After the declaration of independence of Algeria in 1962, almost all the Catalan speakers fled the country to Northern Catalonia (as ''[[Pieds-Noirs]]''), or to Alacant.{{sfn|Marfany|2002}}

Nowadays, France only recognizes French as an official language. Nevertheless, on 10 December 2007, the [[General Council of the Pyrénées-Orientales]] officially recognized Catalan as one of the languages of the department<ref name="Charte en faveur du Catalan">{{cite web|url=http://www.cg66.fr/202-charte-en-faveur-du-catalan.htm|title=''Charte en faveur du Catalan''}} {{cite web|url=http://www.cg66.fr/199-la-catalanitat-a-catalunya-nord.htm|title=''La catalanitat a la Catalunya Nord''}}</ref> and seek to further promote it in public life and education.

===Spanish state: 18th to 20th centuries===
[[File:Associació Protectora de l'Ensenyança Catalana.jpg|right|thumb|150px|"Are you already a member of the Associciation for the protection of Catalan language Education?". Well-known poster in favor of Catalan-language education from 1921.]]
[[File:Francoist Speak in Spanish Singn.jpg|thumb|left|150px|"If you are Spanish, speak in Spanish", Catalonia, 1940s. The portrait is dictator [[Francisco Franco]].]]
{{See also|Nueva Planta decrees|Language politics in Spain under Franco|Anti-Catalanism}}

The decline of Catalan continued in the 16th and 17th centuries. The Catalan defeat in the [[War of Spanish Succession]] (1714) iniciated a series of [[Nueva planta decrees|measures]] imposing the use of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in all spheres of public life.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} These included preaching, theater, courts, education, legal documents, and on the telephone.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} In the 20th century these measures were mostly repealed and supplemented by others, like the prohibition of teaching Catalan, or sanctions for refusing to use Spanish.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}

In parallel, however, the 19th century saw a Catalan literary revival (''[[Renaixença]]''), which has continued up to the present day.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} This period starts with [[Bonaventura Carles Aribau|Aribau]]'s ''Ode to the Homeland'' (1833); followed in the second half of the 19th century, and the early 20th by the work of [[Jacint Verdaguer|Verdaguer]] (poetry), [[Narcís Oller|Oller]] (realist novel), and [[Àngel Guimerà|Guimerà]] (drama).{{sfn|Costa Carreras|2007|pp=10-11}}

In the 19th century, the region of [[Carche]], in the [[province of Murcia]] was repopulated with Catalan speakers from the [[Land of Valencia]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2005|p=1}}

The [[Second Spanish Republic]] (1931-1939) saw a brief period of tolerance, with most restrictions against Catalan being lifted.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} However, the establishment of the [[Francoist Spain|Francoist dictatorship]] lead to a total ban on the language in 1940.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} Despite some gradual relaxations allowing the publication of some books and magazines, Catalan was excluded from all public institutions until the adoption of the [[Spanish constitution|1978 constitution]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}

===Present day===
Since the [[Spanish transition to democracy]] (1975–1982), Catalan has been institutionalizated as an official language, language of education, and language of mass media; all of which have contributed to its increased prestige.{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}} In [[Catalonia]], there is no parallel of a large, [[bilingualism|bilingual]], [[Europe]]an, [[Stateless nation|non-state]] speech community.{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}} The teaching of Catalan is mandatory in all schools.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} There is also some intergenerational shift towards Catalan.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}

In [[Andorra]], Catalan has always been the sole official language.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} Since the promulgation of the [[Constitution of Andorra|1993 constitution]], several Andorranization policies have been enforced, like Catalan medium education.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}

On the other hand, there are several [[language shift]] processes currently taking place. In [[Northern Catalonia]], Catalan has followed the same trend as the other minority languages of [[France]], with most of its native speakers being 60 or older (as of 2004).{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} Catalan is studied as a foreign language by 30% of the primary education estudents, and by 15% of the secondary.{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}} The cultural associacion ''[[La Bressola]]'' promotes a network of community-run schools engaged in Catalan language immersion programs.

In the [[Alicante province]] Catalan is being replaced by [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and in [[Alghero]] by [[Italian language|Italian]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2003|p=207}} There are also well ingrained [[diglossia|diglossic]] attitudes against Catalan in the [[Valencian Community]], [[Ibiza]], and to a lesser extent, in the rest of the [[Balearic islands]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2010|p=191}}

==Classification and relationship with other Romance languages==
[[File:Romance-lg-classification-en.png|thumb|326x326px|Chart of Romance languages based on structural and comparative criteria (not on socio-functional ones). Koryakov (2001) includes Catalan in [[Occitano-Romance]], distinct from [[Ibero-Romance]].{{sfn|Koryakov|2001}}]]
The ascription of Catalan to the [[Occitano-Romance languages|Occitano-Romance]] branch of [[Gallo-Romance languages]] is not shared by all linguists, particularly those from the Castillian sphere, like [[Menéndez Pidal]].

According to [[Pierre Bec|Pèire Bèc]], its specific classification is as follows:
* [[Romance languages]]
** [[Italo-Western languages]]
*** [[Western Romance languages]]
**** [[Gallo-Iberian languages]]
***** [[Gallo-Romance languages]] (alternatively classified as [[Ibero-Romance languages|Ibero-Romance language]])
****** [[Occitano-Romance languages]] (alternatively classified as [[Iberian Romance languages#Family tree|East Iberian language]])
******* Catalan language

Catalan bears varying degrees of similarity to the linguistic varieties subsumed under the cover term ''[[Occitan language]]'' (see also [[Occitan#Differences between Occitan and Catalan|differences between Occitan and Catalan]] and [[Gallo-Romance languages]]). Thus, as it should be expected from closely related languages, Catalan today shares many traits with other Romance languages.

===Relationship with other Western Romance languages===
Catalan shares many traits with the other neighboring [[Romance languages]] ([[Italian language|Italian]], [[Sardinian language|Sardinian]], Occitan, and Spanish).{{sfn|Wheeler|2005|p=1}} However, despite being mostly situated in the [[Iberian Peninsula]], Catalan has marked differences with the [[Ibero-Romance]] group ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) in terms of [[pronunciation]], grammatical, and especially vocabulary; showing instead general affinity towards [[Gallo-Romance]] ([[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Occitan language|Occitan]], etc.).<ref name=":11" />{{sfn|Jud|1925}}{{sfn|Colón|1993|pp=33–35}}{{sfn|Moll|1958|p=47}}{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=632}}{{sfn|Feldhausen|2010|p=4}}{{sfn|Schlösser|2005|p=60f}} These similarities are most notable with Occitan.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=632}}{{sfn|Feldhausen|2010|p=4}}{{sfn|Schlösser|2005|p=60f}}

According to [[Ethnologue]], the lexical similarity between Catalan and other Romance languages is 87% with Italian, 85% with Portuguese and Spanish, 76% with Ladin, 75% with Sardinian, and 73% with Romanian.<ref name="e17" />
