==Grammar==
{{Main|Catalan grammar}}

The grammar of Catalan is similar to other [[Romance languages]]. Features include:{{sfn|Swan|2001|pp=97-98}}
*Use of [[definite article|definite]] and [[indefinite article|indefinite]] [[article (grammar)|article]]s.{{sfn|Swan|2001|p=97-98}}
*[[Noun]]s, [[adjective]]s, [[pronoun]]s, and [[article (grammar)|article]]s are [[inflection|inflected]] for [[grammatical gender|gender]] (masculine and feminine), and [[grammatical number|number]] (singular and plural). There is no [[case (grammar)|case]] inflexion, except in pronouns.{{sfn|Swan|2001|p=97-98}}
*[[Verb]]s are highly inflected for [[person (grammar)|person]], [[number (grammar)|number]], [[tense (grammar)|tense]], [[aspect (grammar)|aspect]], and [[mood (grammar)|mood]] (including a [[subjunctive mood|subjunctive]]).{{sfn|Swan|2001|p=97-98}}
*There are no [[modal auxiliary|modal auxiliaries]].{{sfn|Swan|2001|p=97-98}}
*Word order is freer than in English.{{sfn|Swan|2001|p=97-98}}

===Gender and number inflection===
[[File:Flexió of word Gat.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Gender and number inflection of the word ''gat'' ("cat").]]
{|
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Regular noun with definite article: ''el gat'' ("the cat")
|-
! !! masculine !! feminine
|-
! singular
| ''el gat'' || ''la gat'''a'''''
|-
! plural
| ''els gat'''s''''' || ''les gat'''es'''''
|}
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Adjective with 4 forms: <br>''verd'' ("green")
|-
! !! masculine !! feminine
|-
! singular
| ''verd'' || ''verd'''a'''''
|-
! plural
| ''verd'''s''''' || ''verd'''es'''''
|}
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Adjective with 3 forms: <br>''feliç'' ("happy")
|-
! !! masculine !! feminine
|-
! singular
| colspan="2" | ''feliç''
|-
!plural
| ''feliç'''os''''' || ''felic'''es'''''
|}
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Adjective with 2 forms: <br>''{{not a typo|indiferent}}'' ("indifferent")
|-
! !! masculine !! feminine
|-
! singular
| colspan="2" | ''{{not a typo|indiferent}}''
|-
!plural
| colspan="2" | ''{{not a typo|indiferent}}'''s'''''
|}
|}
In [[gender inflection]], the most notable feature is (compared to [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or [[Italian language|Italian]]), the disapparition of the typical [[masculine]] [[suffix]] ''-o''. Thus, the alternance of ''-o''/''-a'', has been replaced by ''ø''/''-a''.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}} There are only a few exceptions, like ''minso''/''minsa'' ("scarce").{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}} Many not completely predictable morphological alternations may occur, like:{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}}
* Affrication: ''bo'''ig'''''/''bo'''j'''<u>a</u>'' ("insane") vs. ''lle'''ig'''''/''lle'''tj'''<u>a</u>'' ("ugly")
* Loss of ''n'': ''pla''/''pla'''n'''<u>a</u>'' ("flat") vs. ''sego'''n'''''/''sego'''n'''<u>a</u>'' ("second")
* [[Final obstruent devoicing]]: ''senti'''t'''''/''senti'''d'''<u>a</u>'' ("felt") vs. ''di'''t'''''/''di'''t'''<u>a</u>'' ("said")

Catalan has few [[suppletion|suppletive]] couplets, like Italian and Spanish, and unlike French. Thus, Catalan has ''noi''/''noia'' ("boy"/"girl") and ''gall''/''gallina'' ("cock"/"hen"), whereas French has ''garçon''/''fille'' and ''coq''/''poule''.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}}

There is a tendency to abandon traditionally gender-invariable adjectives in favour of marked ones, something prevalent in [[Occitan]] and French. Thus, one can find ''bullent''/''bullenta'' ("boiling") in constrast with traditional ''bullent''/''bullent''.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}}

Like in the other Western Romance languages, the main plural expression is the suffix ''-s'', which may create morphological alternations akin the ones found in gender inflection, albeit more rarely.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630}}
The most important one is the addition of ''-o-'' before certain consonant groups, a [[phonetic]] phenomenon that does not affect feminine forms: ''el pols''/''els polsos'' ("the pulse"/"the pulses") vs. ''la pols''/''les pols'' ("the dust"/"the dusts").{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=630-631}}

===Determiners===
[[File:Begur - Plaça de la Vila - Catalunya.jpg|right|150px|thumb|Sign in the town square of [[Begur, Spain|Begur]], Catalonia, Spain. In ''Plaça de la vila'' (literally "square of the town"), since the noun ''vila'' ("town") is feminine singular, the definite article carries the corresponding form, ''la'' ("the").]]
{|
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Definite article in Standard Catalan <br>(elided forms in brackets){{sfn|Fabra|1926|pp=29-30}}
|-
! !! masculine !! feminine
|-
! singular
| '''el''' ('''l<nowiki>'</nowiki>''') || '''la''' ('''l<nowiki>'</nowiki>''')
|-
! plural
| '''els''' || '''les'''
|}
|
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|+Contractions of the definite article
|-
! colspan="2" rowspan="2"|
! colspan="3" |preposition
|-
! a !! de !! per
|-
! rowspan="2" |article || el
| '''al''' ('''a l<nowiki>'</nowiki>''') || '''del''' ('''de l<nowiki>'</nowiki>''') || '''pel''' ('''per l<nowiki>'</nowiki>''')
