|}

The inflection of determinatives is complex, specially because of the high number of elisions, but is similar to the neighboring languages.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}} Catalan has more contractions of preposition + article than [[Spanish language|Spanish]], like ''dels'' ("of + the [plural]"), but not as many as [[Italian language|Italian]] (which has ''sul'', ''col'', ''nel'', etc.).{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}}

Central Catalan has abandoned almost completely unstressed possessives (''mon'', etc.) in favour of constructions of article + stressed forms (''el meu'', etc.), a feature shared with Italian.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}}

===Personal pronouns===
{| class="wikitable"  style="text-align:center; float:right;"
|+Catalan stressed pronouns{{sfn|Fabra|1926|p=42}}
! colspan=2 | &nbsp; !! singular !! plural
|-
! colspan=2 | 1st person
| ''jo'', ''mi'' || ''nosaltres''
|-
! rowspan=3 | 2nd person !! informal
| ''tu'' || ''vosaltres''
|-
! formal
| ''vostè''||''vostès''
|-
! respectful
| colspan=2 |(''vós'')<ref>Archaic in most dialects.</ref>
|-
! rowspan=2 | 3rd person !! masculine
| ''ell'' || ''ells''
|-
! feminine
| ''ella'' || ''elles''
|}
{{Main|Catalan personal pronouns}}
The morphology of Catalan personal pronouns is complex, specially in unstressed forms, which are numerous (13 distinct forms, compared to 11 in Spanish or 9 in Italian; French has such a different system that comparisons are not feasible). {{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}} Features include the neuter gender (''ho'') and the great degree of freedom when combining different unstressed pronouns (65 combinations).{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}}

The Catalan pronouns exhibit [[T–V distinction]], like all other Romance languages (and most European languages, but not English). This feature implies the use of a different set of second person pronouns for formality.

This flexibility allows Catalan to use [[extraposition]] extensively, much more than French or Spanish. Thus, Catalan can have ''m'hi recomanaren'' ("they recommended me to him"), whereas in French one must say ''ils m'ont recommandé à lui'', and Spanish ''me recomendaron a él''.{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}} This allows the placement of almost any nominal term as a sentence [[Topic–comment|topic]], without having to use so often the [[passive voice]] (as in French or [[English language|English]]), or identifying the [[direct object]] with a [[preposition]] (as in Spanish).{{sfn|Enciclopèdia Catalana|p=631}}
{{clear}}

===Verbs===
